            <p>C. D. SPIVAK&#44; M. D.&#44;<lb/>
                338 SPRUCE ST.<lb/></p>
            <p>Philadelphia&#44; Dec 9 1890<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Dr. S. Morais.<lb/>
                Esteemed sir&#45;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>The bearer Miss Kigrin desires to<lb/> follow in the path of Miss Charsky.  From<lb/> the subjoined letter to me you will see<lb/> that I have placed a Russian girl in<lb/> the Bloomsburg Normal School.  I am<lb/> in receipt of letters from there that she is<lb/> making good progress&#44; is well liked by<lb/> all the professors and was presented with<lb/> Webster&#39;s Dictionary.  I trust if Miss Kigrin<lb/> enters same such school she will prove<lb/> to be a good scholar.  She has decided to<lb/> go to <del>some</del> one of the normal schools<lb/> herself&#44; present her case to the superin&#45;<lb/>tendent&#44; and ask him that her tuition shall<lb/> be paid by herself after she graduates as<lb/> teacher.  These terms were originally granted<lb/> to Miss Charsky.<lb/></p>
            <p>What she wishes now is&#44; a few<lb/></p>
            
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>letters of recommendation from some<lb/> prominent people.<lb/></p>
            <p>I hope you will not refuse<lb/> to aid the girl by giving her a letter.<lb/>  With great esteem<lb/> yours obediently&#44;<lb/> Chas D. Spivak<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
